{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522416"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13828"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13828"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.06,0.06,0.71,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49340"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6445"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34586"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1810"},{"type":"tags","id":"2139"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12732"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49340"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about white lines on his fingernails. He first noticed these changes about two months ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a carpenter and reports no recent changes in his work routine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Inspection of his fingers shows the appearance in the photograph (Image). The lines do not disappear when pressure is applied to the nail. There is no nail bed tenderness, and the surrounding skin appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Koilonychia","Onycholysis","Subungual exostosis","Leukonychia","Trachyonychia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pattern of multiple horizontal white lines across the nail plates of his index fingers and thumbs is consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eleukonychia\u003C/strong\u003E. More precisely, this patient presents with striate leukonychia, characterised by white lines or bands across the nail plate. This condition is often caused by repeated minor trauma to the nail matrix, which is consistent with the patient\u0027s occupation as a carpenter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKoilonychia\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as \u0027spoon nails\u0027, refers to abnormally thin nails that lose their convexity and become concave. This condition is often associated with iron deficiency anaemia and is not consistent with the white lines described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnycholysis\u003C/strong\u003E is the separation of the nail plate from the nail bed. It typically starts at the distal end of the nail and progresses proximally. The description of white lines across the nail does not match this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubungual exostosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a bony outgrowth that occurs beneath the nail. It typically presents as a painful nodule that can distort the nail plate. The absence of pain or visible nail deformity makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrachyonychia\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as \u0027rough nails\u0027, is characterised by excessive longitudinal ridging of the nail plate, giving it a rough and sandpapered appearance. This does not match the description of white lines seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeukonychia can be classified as true leukonychia (where the abnormality is in the nail plate) or apparent leukonychia (where the nail bed is affected). Striate leukonychia, as seen in this case, is a form of true leukonychia. It is commonly seen in individuals whose hobbies or occupations involve repetitive trauma to the nails. The condition is typically benign and self-resolving once the underlying cause is addressed. In this case, advising the patient on proper hand protection during work may help prevent further occurrences.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Leukonychia is characterised by white discolouration of the nail plate, often due to repeated trauma.","Striate leukonychia presents as white lines or bands across the nail and is commonly seen in occupations which involve repetitive nail trauma.","Leukonychia is typically benign and self-resolving once the underlying cause is addressed."],"references":["Iorizzo M, Starace M, Pasch MC. Leukonychia: What Can White Nails Tell Us? Am J Clin Derm 2022; 23:177\u201393"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34586"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13828"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20775"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20775"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Z7ZJPlvAjGLw0I53WK0cFSTrq34bhP.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Z7ZJPlvAjGLw0I53WK0cFSTrq34bhP.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34586"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-28T08:01:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-28T08:01:44+09:30"},"relation